First HODL — BC Registration
Bencal Holdings Inc. ("Bencal"), a corporation to be incorporated under the Business Corporations Act (British Columbia).

Governing Documents

-Articles of Incorporation
-Shareholders Agreement
-Financial Statements
-Allocation and Sales Agreement (CAD $3,000,000)

Key Terms

Directors: Bencal shall be governed by a board of two (2) directors, Ben and Caleb. All board resolutions shall require unanimous approval of the directors.

Corporate Secretary: Caleb shall serve as Corporate Secretary and sole authorized signatory and spokesperson of Bencal. No other officers.

Holdings: Bencal shall hold the following assets:

-10% of the issued and outstanding shares of Ambassadors Direct 1 Inc.
-10% of the issued and outstanding units of Ambassadors Direct 2 Limited Partnership
-1 share in Ambassadors Direct 2 Inc. (General Partner)

Final Sale: The parties may exit or dissolve Bencal through any of the following three mechanisms:

(a) Shotgun Buyout: Either director may trigger a shotgun buyout at any time by delivering written notice to the other, naming a price per share of Bencal. Upon receipt, the other party must elect within thirty (30) days to either buy the triggering party's shares or sell their own shares at the named price. Failure to elect within thirty (30) days shall be deemed an election to sell.

(b) Scheduled Review: On the tenth (10th) anniversary of incorporation and every five (5) years thereafter, either party may formally propose a full wind-up and sale of all Bencal assets. Upon such proposal, the other party shall have thirty (30) days to either agree to the wind-up or acquire the proposing party's shares at fair market value. If no agreement is reached within thirty (30) days, the wind-up shall proceed and all assets shall be sold in an orderly manner.

(c) Voluntary Wind-Up: At any time, both directors may unanimously agree to wind up Bencal and sell all assets, with proceeds distributed pro-rata to each shareholder.

WCP Allocation and Sales Agreement: Bencal is authorized to sell WCP common shares to accredited investors, on a per-subscriber cap of $100,000, at a commission of 10%, up to an aggregate maximum of $3,000,000, for a period to be determined and specified in the Allocation and Sales Agreement.


SPV-1 — BC Registration
Ambassadors Direct 1 Inc. (the "Ambassadors"), a corporation to be incorporated under the Business Corporations Act (British Columbia).

Governing Documents

-Term Sheet
-Articles of Incorporation
-Shareholders Agreement
-Subscription Agreement
-Risk Acknowledgement Form
-Financial Statements
-Private Market Agency Agreement
-Allocation and Sales Agreement (CAD $3,000,000)
-Referral Agreement

Key Terms 

Directors: A board of three (3) directors — two (2) appointed by shareholders and one (1) independent director (the "Independent Director") with no financial interest in WCP, appointed by unanimous vote of the other two. All resolutions require unanimous board approval. Shareholders may remove and replace the Independent Director by simple majority vote.

Corporate Secretary: Rotates annually among the non-independent directors and serves as sole authorized signatory and spokesperson. No other officers.

Share Sales and Transfer: Ambassadors shall offer shares at $1.00 per share until $3,000,000 has been invested in WCP common shares, at which point no further shares shall be issued. Transfers of Ambassadors shares are permitted following the exchange listing of WCP common shares, subject to board approval.

Final Sale: Upon a public listing of Woodfine Capital Projects Inc. ("WCP") on a recognized exchange (the "Listing"), Ambassadors shall sell sufficient WCP common shares to return each shareholder's pro-rata capital at the Listing price (the "Capital Return Sale"). Any remaining WCP common shares held by Ambassadors (the "Residual Position") shall be voted on annually; absent a two-thirds majority to hold, the Residual Position shall be sold that year, and in any event no later than ten (10) years following the Listing date.


SPV-2 — BC Registration
Ambassadors Direct 2 Inc. (the "General Partner") and Ambassadors Direct 2 Limited Partnership (the "Ambassadors LP"), to be incorporated and registered under the Business Corporations Act and Partnership Act (British Columbia).

Governing Documents

-Term Sheet
-Confidential Information Memorandum (Offering Document)
-Articles of Incorporation (General Partner)
-Limited Partnership Agreement
-Shareholders Agreement (General Partner)
-Subscription Agreement (Friends and Family)
-Subscription Agreement (Accredited Investors)
-Risk Acknowledgement Form
-Financial Statements
-Private Market Agency Agreement
-Allocation and Sales Agreement (CAD $25,000,000)
-Referral Agreement

Key Terms

Directors: The General Partner shall be governed by a board of three (3) directors — two (2) appointed by shareholders and one (1) independent director (the "Independent Director") with no financial interest in Professional Centres Canada LP, appointed by unanimous vote of the other two. All resolutions require unanimous board approval. Shareholders may remove and replace the Independent Director by simple majority vote.

Corporate Secretary: Rotates annually among the non-independent directors and serves as sole authorized signatory and spokesperson of the General Partner. No other officers.

Unit Sales and Transfer: Ambassadors LP shall offer units at $100.00 per unit until $25,000,000 has been invested in ProfessionalCentres Canada LP Investment Units, at which point no further units shall be issued. Transfers of Ambassadors LP units are permitted following the Crystallization Date, subject to board approval.

Distributions: Ambassadors LP shall distribute 100% of all amounts received from ProfessionalCentres Canada LP, less the reasonable expenses of the General Partner, to LP unitholders on a pro-rata basis quarterly. Distributions are automatic and are not subject to any Annual Meeting vote.

Residual Position and Capital Return Sale: The Investment Units held by Ambassadors LP (the "Residual Position") shall be held for a minimum period of seven (7) years from the date of first unit issuance, during which no disposition or crystallization may occur. From year seven (7), the General Partner may declare the crystallization period complete (the "Crystallization Date"); if no such declaration has been made by the tenth (10th) anniversary of the first unit issuance, crystallization shall be deemed to have occurred automatically, and the General Partner's unilateral right to execute the Capital Return Sale shall lapse, requiring majority LP unitholder approval for any disposition. Upon the Crystallization Date, the General Partner shall sell sufficient Investment Units to return each LP unitholder's pro-rata capital contribution at the prevailing market price (the "Capital Return Sale").

Annual Meeting: Following the Capital Return Sale, LP unitholders shall vote annually at a meeting of the limited partnership (the "Annual Meeting") on whether to sell all, a portion, or none of the remaining Residual Position for the following twelve (12) months. A quorum of a majority of outstanding LP units must be represented for any vote to be valid; absent quorum the Annual Meeting shall be postponed to the following year and the Residual Position shall be retained. Where quorum is achieved, the Residual Position shall be sold that year unless two-thirds (2/3) of units represented vote to hold for a further twelve (12) months.